rdshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Saye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Say  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Saje</b>: nickname for someone with very dark, sooty hair, derived from the root of <i>sajast</i> ‘sooty’, or directly from <i>saja</i> ‘soot’.","West African (Liberia): from the personal name <i>Saye</i>, found among the Mano (Mah) people, denoting a first-born boy."],"variants":[{"name":"Say","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Sai in Orne or Say in Indre, France, perhaps so called from a Gaulish personal name <i>Saius</i> + the Latin locative suffix <i>-acum</i> (see also French name 3 below).","English: nickname, perhaps for someone who made or sold say, a type of woollen cloth, or for an habitual wearer of clothes made of this material, from Middle English <i>sai(e)</i> ‘say’ (Old French <i>saie</i>, from Latin <i>saga</i>, plural of <i>sagum</i> ‘military cloak’). See also   Sayer  .","French (southern): topographic name from <i>saix</i> (from Latin <i>saxum</i>) ‘rock’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example, Say in Loire, Saix in Tarn and Vienne, Le Saix in Hautes-Alpes, or Les Saix in Isère."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de Saye III was born in 1210, in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with William De Saye III. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1210–":"1210–Surnud","1207–Male":"1207–Surnud","1235–1308":"1235–1308","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1210":"1210","about 1235":"umbes 1235","1308":"1308","1207":"1207","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1210–":"1210–Kuollut","1207–Male":"1207–Kuollut","1235–1308":"1235–1308","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1210":"1210","about 1235":"noin 1235","1308":"1308","1207":"1207","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England"},"fr":{"1210–":"1210–Décédée","1207–Male":"1207–Décédé","1235–1308":"1235–1308","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1210":"1210","about 1235":"environ 1235","1308":"1308","1207":"1207","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de Saye III est née en 1210, à Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec William De Saye III. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1210–":"1210–Verstorben","1207–Male":"1207–Verstorben","1235–1308":"1235–1308","1210–Female":"1210–Verstorben","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1210":"1210","about 1235":"um 1235","1308":"1308","1207":"1207","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William de Saye III wurde 1210 in Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England geboren. Sie hatte mit William De Saye III mindestens 1 Tochter. Sie starb in ihrem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1210–":"1210–Desede","1207–Male":"1207–Desede","1235–1308":"1235–1308","1210–Female":"1210–Desede","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"